@node disclaimer "DISCLAIMER"
PPMtoSCR is provided "AS IS", without warranty of any kind either expressed
or implied.  It has proven to be stable in everyday use, but even so you
still use this program at YOUR OWN RISK.  I will not accept responsibility
for loss of data, damage or anything else caused either directly or
indirectly by PPMtoSCR.

Modified copies of PPMtoSCR must not be distributed.  I have purposely not
included the source code in this archive for that reason*.  Please don't ask
for it unless you have a @{b}very@{ub} good reason (eg. if you think I've
discontinued development, and want to take the project over or something)

PPMtoSCR is @{b}not@{ub} in any way based on the source code for Blood's
BMP2SPEC program.  Neither is it anything to do with the NetPBM
distribution.
(although it does optionally use a couple of programs from there)


* The fact that the source is in a complete mess, with "comments" (ie. old 
  bits of code) floating around and that even I have trouble understanding
  what's going on has got absolutely nothing to do with it.  Probably.

Bad programmers, like good chefs, never reveal their sources (sauces).

Sorry, I meant *good* programmers.  Tch, eh?
@endnode

@node intro "Introduction to PPMtoSCR"
OK.  You're probably all wondering what PPMtoSCR actually does.  In fact,
half of you are probably wondering what a PPM actually is. Or a SCR.  Or
both (in which case, you've left me wondering why you downloaded this in the
first place).

PPMtoSCR quite obviously converts a PPM to a SCR.  It does more than just
that, though - it can put header information on the SCR file, to make it
into a .bytes, .tap or ZX82 instead.  It can take an IFF (or even Datatype
image, if you have WB3) file as input and transparently convert it to a PPM.
It can also apply scaling, to make sure your picture is exactly the right
size. 

But why did I create this?  Didn't I port BMP2SPEC over to the Amiga about
two weeks ago?*  Well, yes.  I did.  But BMP2SPEC, despite doing exactly what
it says on the tin, has several shortcomings.  Not least because it was
designed to run on a PC;

1. It runs out of stack space.
PPMtoSCR does not.

2. It can't do colour.
Although mapping colours to a very limited Spectrum palette and format is
perhaps not going to produce amazing results, it's nice to have the option
there.  PPMtoSCR can convert colour pictures, and if you don't like the way
it maps the colours then you can tell it to stop.  Or tweak it a bit.  Or
save your original image out in monochrome/dithered.

3. It takes a horrible graphics format designed for Windoze.
PPMtoSCR takes PPM files instead.  Although not the most well-known format
on the planet, the whole point of PPMs is that they are portable.  As such,
you can get programs which convert most major graphics formats (including
BMP) to PPM.  This allows you to convert files in various different formats
to SCR, and is the closest I can get to Datatypes without actually using
them.  PPMtoSCR can also handle IFF files transparently.

4. It only saves in Z80 .tap format
PPMtoSCR can save raw screen files, .tap and the .header/.bytes format used
by most (if not all) Amiga Speccy emulators.  It can also save ZX82s, which
a number of Spectrum utilities on the Amiga use.

5. It was CLI only
Little conversion utilities don't really need a GUI, but file requesters are
nice and make programs a lot friendlier.  So PPMtoSCR has file requesters.

6. It needed an input file of exactly the right size
PPMtoSCR now has "dynamic re-scaling" through the use of pnmscale.  Your
source file can be any size, and it will always be scaled to the proper
dimensions before conversion.

7. It was not configurable
Although BMP2SPEC didn't have any real need for configuration, PPMtoSCR
does.  You can tweak all the colour mapping, switching both BRIGHT and all
colour on and off, or simply adjusting the sensitivity.

8. It didn't support FLASH!
Although nobody will actually use it anyway... (sighs with a sudden
realisation that hours of hard work have been a waste of time)

OK, so I could fix some of those things.  But I decided to write a
completely new program instead.


* Actually, it was a @{i}bit@{ui} longer than that.
@endnode

@node distrib "Distribution"
You can distribute this as much as you like, but please note the following
permissions and restrictions;

You @{b}must@{ub} distribute this documentation with PPMtoSCR. Everything
else included in the archive does @{b}not@{ub} need to be kept with the main
program.

You @{b}must not@{ub} distribute the OS3 Preview @{b}without@{ub} the
standard version.  The OS3 preview does not work very well and will give
people a poor view of what PPMtoSCR can do.

Aminet, NVG and World of Spectrum are perfectly entitled to distribute
PPMtoSCR through FTP.  Everyone else is allowed to do that as well,
providing the file is accessible by *everybody* at *no cost* (ie. Anonymous
FTP)

Distribution on CD-ROM is perfectly OK.  If you are @{b}not@{ub} mentioned
below and are thinking of distributing PPMtoSCR on a CD made for profit,
then you @{b}must@{ub} ask me first.  I would appreciate a copy of the CD
in question, as if you are making money out of my program, then I believe I
should also get something out of it.  If you don't agree with this, then
don't put it in a compilation.

The following people have my permission to include PPMtoSCR on their CDs.
They are not required to notify me or give me anything, although gifts won't
be refused :-)

1. Aminet
2. Magazines (cover CDs/disks @{i}only@{ui} - not special subscriber disks)
3. Gerard Sweeney
@endnode

@node require "Requirements"
PPMtoSCR uses several features of OS2.0, so you will need an Amiga running
at least Workbench 2.0

I have not been able to test this program on anything below WB3.0

Optionally needed (and included in this archive) are;

ilbmtoppm - if you want ppmtoscr to automatically handle IFFs
pnmscale  - for the "dynamic rescaling" feature.
@{"XtoILBM" link xtoilbm.readme/main}  - for automatic handling of Datatypes pictures

Also recommended is the ZX Datatype, available on Aminet.  Especially if you
want to convert SCRs back to SCRs just to see how well PPMtoSCR works :-)
@endnode

@node install "Installation"
Tch.  Do you really need to read this?  It's OBVIOUS.  Just double-click on
"Install PPMtoSCR".  But remember, kiddies, you need
Commodore/Escom/Amiga In(c|t)'s rather groovy Installer program.

If you don't have it, well, why not?
@endnode

@node usage "Usage Instructions"
I have divided this section of the guide up into several parts;

@{"Getting a suitable input file" link usage-input}
@{"General usage (no args)      " link usage-gen}
@{"Command line arguments       " link usage-cli}
@{"Workbench tooltypes          " link usage-wb}

Please note that during its operation PPMtoSCR may create three temporary
files in T: called ppmtoscr.temp, ppmtoscr.ppm and ppmtoscr.dt.  These will
be removed after PPMtoSCR has finished, but if you have any files of these
names in T: then they will be overwritten without warning.  OK, so it's
unlikely.  But I've warned you just in case.
@endnode

@node usage-input "Obtaining a suitable input file"
Find or draw a picture.  Pictures without lots of shading will generally
convert better.  If the one you want to convert has got a lot of shading,
then dither it down to two colours, and add the colour back in afterwards
(in Spectrum-style blocks).  Saving in @{"greyscale" link alg} mode can also
often improve the resulting image quality.  However, bright and colourful
digitised images can look very good in colour.

It is advised that the source image should have an aspect ratio of 4:3 or
similar (even better if you can cut or scale the picture down to 256x192)
If you do not have pnmscale in your path, or you are operating with
"NOSCALE" turned on, then the picture @{b}must@{ub} be 256x192

Assuming you can't save directly in PPM format, you will then need to run
the picture through a xxxtoppm conversion utility.  These are available on
Aminet in gfx/pbm/ppmbin2.lha.  PPaint's PBM saver is perfectly capable of
saving PPMs, but please save with the BINARY mode ON, and AUTOMATIC switched
OFF - else you are likely to end up with a file that PPMtoSCR can't read.
The PPM file @{b}must@{ub} be a P6 (PPM rawbits/binary) format file.

If you are saving in IFF ILBM, this can be loaded directly into ppmtoscr,
if you have ilbmtoppm (supplied) somewhere in your path.
@endnode

@node usage-gen "General Usage Information"
OK.  Now it's time to actually get your picture into a Spectrum format.  Run
PPMtoSCR through a Shell/CLI window or double-click on it.  More about each
method can be found in the sections @{"CLI usage" link usage-cli} and @{"WB usage" link usage-wb}

You'll see the usual version number/copyright information, quickly followed by
a file requester.  Select the file you have just made, and click Load.  If
it is a valid PPM, IFF or Datatypes image, then the file will be read,
scaled and converted* and a requester will appear.  Simply select the
@{"format" link formats-output} you want the image to be saved as, and a
file requester will appear prompting for a filename.

Enter the save filename - please note that the filename extension NO LONGER
determines the output format as from Version 2.0

If all went OK, you should see the message "conversion done - all ok".
Now load the file into the appropriate program (see @{"output formats" link formats-output}) and
enjoy.

* not necessarily in that order
@endnode

@node usage-cli "Command Line Arguments"
Shell Template:

PPMFILE/A,SCRFILE/A,FORM=SAVEFORMAT/K,COL=COLOURSENSE/K/N,
BRT=BRIGHTSENSE/K/N,WHT=WHITESENSE/K/N,RED=FLASHRED/K/N,GRN=FLASHGREEN/K/N,
BLU=FLASHBLUE/K/N,NOSCALE/S,GREYSCALE/S,NOBRIGHT/S,NOSMOOTH/S,QUIET/S


PPMFILE:*   This is your input PPM (or IFF/DT) format file

SCRFILE:*   This is the path and filename of the resulting file.  Note that
            the filename's extension NO LONGER determines output format. 
          
SAVEFORMAT: Specifies the output format.  See @{"output formats" link formats-output}

COL=COLOURSENSE/K/N,BRT=BRIGHTSENSE/K/N,WHT=WHITESENSE/K/N

Colour mapping options.  See @{"colour mapping" link alg} and @{"tooltypes" link usage=wb}

RED=FLASHRED/K/N,GRN=FLASHGREEN/K/N,BLU=FLASHBLUE/K/N

Set when to use the FLASH attribute.  See @{"FLASH mode" link flash}

NOSCALE:   This will stop ppmtoscr calling pnmscale to scale your source
           image.  You MUST supply this switch if "pnmscale" is not in your
           command path/current directory.
         
GREYSCALE: This stops PPMtoSCR from outputting colour images
           
NOBRIGHT:  This prevents PPMtoSCR from using the BRIGHT attribute

NOSMOOTH:  Turns off the @{"smooth mode" link alg}

QUIET:     PPMtoSCR will not display any output except "conversion failed".
           To find out why, you may have to run the same conversion again
           with QUIET switched off

* Required options

Example;

ppmtoscr ram:pic.iff ram:specpic SAVEFORMAT ZX82 NOSCALE

will convert ram:pic.iff to a ZX82 file named specpic, and will NOT scale
the source image down to the correct size.
@endnode

@node usage-wb
Available Tooltypes:
Note that the tooltypes do @{b}not@{ub} exactly correspond with the CLI
arguments.

COLOURSENSE= <value> [default = 20]
BRIGHTSENSE= <value> [default = 450]
WHITESENSE = <value> [default = 200]

These set the colour levels at which point PPMtoSCR detects colour, white
from black and the BRIGHT attribute.  Please note that setting any of these
to 0 will put them to the default.  See @{"colour mapping" link alg} for
information on how to use these.

FLASHRED=<value>
FLASHGRN=<value>
FLASHBLU=<value>

These set when to use the FLASH attribute.  See @{"FLASH mode" link flash}.

WINX=<value> [default=0]
WINY=<value> [default=0]

These set the position of the status bar window.

NOSCALE

This turns off the "dynamic re-scaling" feature of PPMtoSCR.  You MUST
supply this switch if "pnmscale" isn't in your path or current directory.

NOBRIGHT

Turns off the BRIGHT attribute matching (same as BRIGHTSENSE=5000).  Please
note that if both BRIGHTSENSE and NOBRIGHT are specified, BRIGHTSENSE will
do nothing.

GREYSCALE

This stops PPMtoSCR from mapping colours (same as COLOURSENSE=5000).  Please
note that if both GREYSCALE and COLOURSENSE are specified, then COLOURSENSE
will do nothing.

NOSMOOTH

This turns off the smoothing feature of PPMtoSCR.  See @{"colour mapping" link alg}

QUIET

This will stop PPMtoSCR from displaying any output.  It is recommended to
ALWAYS set this switch unless you keep getting "conversion failed" errors. 
This only suppresses console output, not requesters.

@endnode

@node formats "File Formats Information"
@{"Input Formats " link formats-input} PPM, IFF and Datatypes
@{"Output Formats" link formats-output} SCR, .bytes, TAP and ZX82
@endnode

@node formats-input "The Input Formats"
@{b}PPM@{ub}
PPM is a Portable Pixel Map.  It is used by the NetPBM distribution programs
to convert between various incompatible formats.  I choose to use this as
the source format because (a) it looked easy to implement and (b) there is a
host of programs in Aminet gfx/pbm to convert files to this format.  It's
the next best thing to Datatypes.  Although those are implemented as well,
for the best of both worlds...

PPMtoSCR can only load "P6" format files: these are PPMs saved with the
"rawbits" option.  Please note that @{i}greyscale@{ui} pictures saved with
PPaint's PBM saver will not save out in the correct format (unless
"automatic" mode is switched off)

@{b}IFF@{ub}
Oh, come on.  You really ought to know what this is.
PPMtoSCR cannot handle IFFs directly - instead it passes them to "ilbmtoppm"
for conversion.  "ilbmtoppm" can handle several different types of IFF
images.

@{b}Datatypes@{ub}
These are a feature of Workbench 3, and are handled by PPMtoSCR through the
programs XtoILBM and ilbmtoppm.  As such, if you do not have XtoILBM,
ilbmtoppm or Workbench 3.0 then any attempt to load DT images will fail.
@endnode

@node formats-output "The Output File Formats"
@{b}SCR@{ub}
SCR is basically no more than a simple file dump of the Spectrum's screen
memory: starting at byte 16384 and lasting for 6912 bytes.  The actual
format of a Spectrum screen is difficult to explain, but if you've ever
watched a Speccy load a screen from tape then you already know the format
anyway.  If you haven't, then just try it.  It's certainly a lot easier than
me attempting to explain it to you.

If you want to view SCR files, then the best thing to try is the ZX
Datatype.

@{b}TAP@{ub}
This is a tape image format used by the emulator Z80 on the PC.

The only emulator on the Amiga that can read these is ZXAM (through an ARexx
script).

@{b}BYTES@{ub} (.header/.bytes)
This is the Amiga's standard format for tape files on disk.

Most, if not all, Amiga Spectrum emulators can read this format.  I don't
think any other platform has an emulator capable of reading them.

@{b}ZX82@{ub}
This is another standard format on the Amiga, which does not quite conform
to how a Spectrum would save data: ie. it has a special header, and the
filename comes from the actual name of the file.  There is also no checksum.
PPMtoSCR can currently only save the non-compressed files.

Speculator, ZXmit and the ZX Datatype can read this format.  There are some
other programs which also use it, and details can be found in the Speculator
documentation.


To read headered SCR files into an emulator, simply set it to the
appropriate load mode and type LOAD "" SCREEN$ [then press return]
This can be achieved in 48K BASIC by pressing the keys;
[J] [Symbol Shift and P] [Symbol Shift and P] [Symbol Shift and Caps Shift]
[Symbol Shift and K] [Return]
@endnode

@node future "Future Plans"
The main plan is to use some Datatypes code Joe Mackay is kindly writing for
me (thanks!) to create...
@{b}DATATYPE-TO-SPECTRUM@{ub}
(obviously a better name is in order - any suggestions?)

Then PPMtoSCR will be slightly renamed to ppmtoscr, stripped of its
Workbench support, and pushed, screaming, into a darkened room known as
"gfx/pbm".

In other words, there will be two programs: this one, slightly reduced in
size, and designed to integrate with the NetPBM package.
And this one, with removed PPM support and no external programs needed (but
OS3 only) which should convert directly from Datatypes to SCR etc.

OS3 bods can use either.
OS2 peeps can use NetPBM/ppmtoscr, of course.
OS1.x users can upgrade.


This is a list of other things I might possibly add for the next release:

Greatly improve the OS3 colour mapping version

Does anyone know of a Datatype -> PPM conversion utility?  This will speed
up DT conversion.  Although XtoILBM seems to be a very fast program anyway. 
ilbmtoppm isn't, though.  Oh, and dttoppm doesn't seem to work properly.

A progress bar.

Dither pics down to Spectrum palette, through ppmdither.  But it doesn't
give too good results after going through PPMtoSCR...

Implementing an environmental variable for the default output format, colour
modes etc. (I had this implemented for about 10 minutes, but I removed it)

"Everything else is PAPER" option (see colour mapping section)

More presets for the favourite SENSE options (like the current GREYSCALE
and NOBRIGHT switches).  If I can think of any.  ALLBRIGHT comes to mind.

GUI.  Although I might leave that to some third party... (small hint there)

Change the BRIGHT detection so it only considers the brightness of INK and
PAPER, not every colour in the block.  (easy to add for OS3 version...)

Dynamic Contrast for checking the brightness of the picture and selecting
the correct level for BRIGHT to make everything look good.

Saving direct to cassette tape (!)

Of course, if you have any other suggestions...
@endnode

